tChapter 20 White Folks, Gay Men, and Straight Black Folks Don’t Come -- tChapter 21 The Drama of Owning a Queer Bar -- tChapter 22 Women First, Lesbians Second, But Everyone’s Welcome -- tPart Five. Cruisy Men’s Bars -- tChapter 23 Democratizing Sexy Community -- tChapter 24 We Were a Bear Bar. The Trans Community Was Extremely Forgiving -- tChapter 25 Rebranding The Eagle for the Next Generations -- tChapter 26 Leathermen at Drag Bingo -- tChapter 27 Queering the Gay Strip Club -- tPart Six. How to Save a Gay Bar -- tChapter 28 Crowdfunding While Black -- tChapter 29 Nonprofit Ownership Means We Celebrate Pride Every Week -- tChapter 30 Part of an Otherwise-Straight Hospitality Group -- tChapter 31 The Benefits of Employee Ownership Caven Enterprises’ JR’s, Sue Ellen’s, TMC, S4, and Rose Room DALLAS, TEXAS -- tChapter 32 #SaveTheGayBars from Another Pandemic -- tPart Seven. National Monuments -- tChapter 33 National Archive -- tChapter 34 National Memorial -- tChapter 35 Municipal Landmark in Exile -- tChapter 36 AIDS Altars in Plain Sight -- tChapter 37 A Post-Gay, Not-Gay, Very Gay, Un-Bar -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGay bars have been closing by the hundreds. The story goes that increasing mainstream acceptance of LGBTQ+ people, plus dating apps like Grindr and Tinder, have rendered these spaces obsolete. Beyond that, rampant gentrification in big cities has pushed gay bars out of the neighborhoods they helped make hip. Who Needs Gay Bars? considers these narratives, accepting that the answer for some might be: maybe nobody. And yet. Jarred by the closing of his favorite local watering hole in Cleveland, Ohio, Greggor Mattson embarks on a journey across the country to paint a much more complex picture of the cultural significance of these spaces, inside "big four" gay cities, but also beyond them. No longer the only places for their patrons to socialize openly, Mattson finds in them instead a continuously evolving symbol; a physical place for feeling and challenging the beating pulse of sexual progress. From the historical archives of Seattle's Garden of Allah, to the outpost bars in Texas, Missouri or Florida that serve as community hubs for queer youth—these are places of celebration, where the next drag superstar from Alaska or Oklahoma may be discovered. They are also fraught grounds for confronting the racial and gender politics within and without the LGBTQ+ community. The question that frames this story is not asking whether these spaces are needed, but for whom, earnestly exploring the diversity of folks and purposes they serve today. Loosely informed by the Damron Guide, the so-called "Green Book" of gay travel, Mattson logged 10,000 miles on the road to all corners of the United States. His destinations are sometimes thriving, sometimes struggling, but all offering intimate views of the wide range of gay experience in America: POC, white, trans, cis; past, present, and future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGay barszUnited States. 0aGay peoplezUnited StatesxSocial life and customs. 0aSexual minoritieszUnited StatesxSocial life and customs. 0aSexual minority communityzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aGay.  aLGBTQ.  aalcohol.  abars.  aclubs.  adrinking.  aleisure.  alesbian.  anightlife.  aqueer.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023 Englishz978311131909408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK